<STNO>0096</STNO>
IT'S ALL ABOUT THE MONEY    * SOME policymakers blame Asia's crisis on cronyism, but this does not explain the sudden collapse of competitive economies. 
<STNO>0097</STNO>
* More important is the short-run global financial cycle, which is characterised by sharp swings in the flows of international capital. 
<STNO>0098</STNO>
* Between 1994 and 1996, international banks put an estimated US$264 billion of net funds into 25 emerging economies. 
<STNO>0099</STNO>
* In 1997, they withdrew just as suddenly, which precipitated the crisis. 
<STNO>0100</STNO>
* Affected countries became illiquid, their exchange rates collapsed, their banks failed and interest rates sky-rocketed. 
<STNO>0101</STNO>
They went into deep recession. 
<STNO>0102</STNO>
* Also, when a country's debt-reserve ratio is high, as was the case with many Asian economies, it is susceptible to financial panic, which can be triggered by an overvalued currency collapsing. 
<STNO>0103</STNO>
Creditors scramble to get out first. 
<STNO>0104</STNO>
* Similarly, recovery is faster than expected. 
